 centuries. Made to Order addresses how breeding methodology evolved, what characterized the aims of breeding, and the way structures were put in place to regulate the occupation. Illustrated by case studies on important farm animals and companion species, the book presents a synthetic overview of livestock breeding as a whole. It gives considerable emphasis to genetics and animal breeding in the post-1960 period, the relationship between environmental and improvement breeding, and regulation of breeding as seen through pedigrees. In doing so, Made to Order shows how studying the ancient human practice of animal breeding can illuminate the ways in which human thinking, theorizing, and evolving characterize our interactions with all-natural processes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aHuman-animal relationshipsxHistory. 0aLivestockxBreedingxHistory. 7aTechnology & Engineering / Agriculture / Animal Husbandry.2bisacsh  aagriculture.  aanimal agriculture.  aanimal disease.  abreeding science.  acows.  aculture of breeding.  adomestic animals.  afarming.  agenomics.  ahistory of breeding.  alivestock.  amolecular genetics.  apedigree.  aveterinary medicine.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076715540uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148754162040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487541620423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487541620/original  a978-3-11-076715-5  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_CHCOMSGSEN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CHCOMSGSEN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK